{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558868/1945092101/0249.xml":{"full_text":"JAP -GUINEA PIG' FOR ATOMIC BOMB\nThe U. S. Navy is reported planning to blast the 32,700-ton Japanese battleship Nagato, above,\nwith atomic bombs,in an experiment that may decide the form of all navies in the future world.\nThe heavily damaged Nagato, only battleship rem aining to the enemy, will be towed 500 miles out\nto sea where atom bombs will be dropped on it to ascertain whether America\u2019s superweapon will\nsink a ship of this sort and the effect of the blast on the water.\nI\nRocky Mountain States Offer Jobs\nFor Thousands Of Peacetime Help\nBy WEBB TROUT\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\n(Third of a Series)\n(Copyright 1945, By United Press)\nDENVER, Colo., Sept. 20.\u2014(U.P.\n\u2014The wheels of reconversion art\nturning swiftly and smooXily ir\nthe Rocky Mountain' west todaj\nat a \u201cjobs-for-all\u201d tempo.\u201d\nReadjustment to peacetime pro\nduction was forging ahead at sue!\na pace that tens of thousands o\njobs were \u2018\u2018going begging\u201d ir\nColorado, New Mexico, Wyoming\nUtah and Montana.\nThe non-industrial states, com\nparatively untouched by the war\ntide of factories that swept thi\nnation four years ago, have en\ncountered few of the thorny prob\nJems of reconversion.\nConsequently, the postwar trenc\nin this region is toward establish\nment of new industries, lumber\ning, petroleum production, live\nstock-raising, and an already pros\nperous tourist business.\nCountless thousands of the re\ngion's labor force will move inti\ngold and silver mines, into vas\nsugar beet fields, lumber camps\nranches, oil fields, departmen'\nstores, cafes, packing houses\nhotels and resorts.\nThis was the outlook in the five\nstate area:\nColorado: Despite the fact tha\u2018\n14.000 workers were displaced ir\nColorado war production centers\u2014\nmost of them in Denver, Puebli\nand Colorado Springs\u2014the state\u2019s\nworker needs still are great. Somi\n9.000 jobs are open in agriculture,\nmining, housing construction, lum\nber camps, department stores,\nrestaurants and reports.\n\"Reconversion is progressing\nvery satisfactorily in Colorado,\u201d\nState Manpower Director L. A\nWest said. \u2018\u2018We have no unem\nployment now, and we don\u2019t ex\npect any\u2014at least m for several\nmonths.\u201d\nWyoming: Unemployment is a\nforeign word here. Wyoming Gov\nernor Lester C. Hunt forecasts s\nfour to five year full-employmenl\nprosperity era, in which thousands\nof jobs will be available in state\nreclamation work, highway build\ning, housing, agriculture and live\nstock, and state wildlife projects.\nFifteen hundred jobs were re\nported open in Cheyenne alone.\nNew Mexico: New Mexico plant\nfor postwar construction are am\nbitious and will transform the\nstate info one of the most moderr\nin the nation. Residential building\nwill run to around $20,000,000 a\nyear\u2014$7,000,000 more than 1939\u2014\nand non-reeidential const luction\nwill hit the $11,000,000 mark, anoth\ner $7,000,000 higher than pre-war\nlevels.\nVast irrigation projects and\nbasic-industry activities also will\nstave off unemployment.\nMontana: Officials report a cur\nrent shortage of 16,000 workers.\nThey are open or soon will be in\n1 the state\u2019s 83,000-acre sugar beet\nharvest and in the sugar proces\nsing mills.\nSeveral plants at Billings, Mon\ntana\u2019s only large war production\ncenter, have reconverted and are\nbegging for hundreds of workers.\nBuilding of the Hungry Horse\ndam in northwest Montana\u2014a $50,\n000,000 project\u2014and work on many\nother state improvements will ab\nsorb thousands of additional work\ners.\nUtah: Employers in Utah have\n15,000 to 18,000 jobs open\u2014most\nof them for \u201crugged male work\ners.\u201d Major postwar problem In\nUtah is conversion of war-born ac\ntivities to peacetime production.\nThe big demand is for agricultural\nworkers and miners.\n(Tomorrow: the southwest).\nNavy Will Not Give Up\nPacific Island Bases\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 20.\u2014(iP)\u2014\nThe Navy disclosed today its in\ntention not to give up any Pacific\nisland bases until a final decision\non their disposition is made.\nThe disclosure was made to the\nHouse Naval committee by Ad\nmiral F. J. Horne, vice chief of\nNaval operations.\nThe Navy has orders, Admiral\nHorne told the committee, not to\nabandon any of the bases but to\nkeep them, at least in caretaker\nstatus, until a final determination\nis made with respect to what is\nlands the United States shall con\ntrol permanently.\nAdmiral Horne and Rear Admiral\n-W. L. Burrough submitted to the\ncommittee a list of major and\nsecondary bases the Navy expects\nto retain permanently after the\nwar. Admiral Burrough emphasized\nthat the list was drawn for \u201cplan\nning\u201d purposes only and was ten\ntative until final arrangements\nfor control of the islands are made.\nThe bases tentatively chosen for\nretention in the Pacific:\nMajor bases: Pearl Harbor,\nGuam-Saipan area, the Philippines,\nManus in the Admiralties.\nSecondary bases: Kodiak, Adak,\nBalboa, Bonins-Volcano group,\nRyukyus, Tutu-Tawitawi, Subic,\nLeyte-Uamar, Palau, Puerto Prin\ncessa, Galapagos, Attu, Johnston\nIsland, Midway, Wake, Samoa,\nEniwetok, Kwajalein, Truk.\nCaretaker-emergency bases:\nDutch Harbor, Canton Island, Pal\nmyra, Majuro, Ulithi.\nIn the Atlantic, Navy plans call\nfor a major base in the Puerto\nSico\u2014Virgin Islands area, and fop\nthese secondary bases:\nArgentia, Bermuda, Guanta\nnamo, Trinidad, Coco Solo.\nCaretaker-emergency \u2018bases in\nthe Atlantic would be located at\nSt. Thomas, Antigua, Georgetown,\nGreat Exuma, Jamaica, and\nSanta Lucia.\nIn continental United States, the\nAdmirals disclosed, these facili\nties are planned for the post-war\nNavy:\nFleet operations areas: Norfolk\nHampton Roads-Chesapeake Bay\narea; New York-Long Island-Nar\nragansett Bay-Casco Bay area;\nSan Pedro\u2014San Diego area; Puget\nSound area.\nSecondary bases: Submarine\nbase at New London, Conn.; am\nphibious bases at San Diego and\nLittle Creek, Va.; sound schools\nat Key West, Fla., and San Diego;\nmine school and mine warfare\ntest station in the Chesapeake\nBay area; advance base depot\nand training scools at Davisville,\nR. I., and Hueneme, Calif.; re\npair base at San Diego, and net\nschool at Tiburon, Calif.\nMost of the Pacific bases named\nby the Admirals coincide with\nthose recently recommended for\nretention by a House Naval sub\ncommittee.\nApproximately 10,000,(F' Christ\nmas trees are cut from American\nwoodlands every December.\nKOREAN SET-UP\nMAY TAKE YEARS\nSEOULv Korea, Sept. 13.\u2014(Cor\nrect)\u2014(U.R)\u2014Maj. Gen. Archibald V.\nArnold, military governor of\nKorea, said today that the Ameri\ncan occupation of Korea may last\nanywhere from ope to 15 years.\n'We will give Korea back to the\nKoreans when they are qualif-ed\nto govern the country,\u201d he said in\nan interview. \u201cI\u2019ve told Koreans\nthat might be in one year, 10\nyears or 15 years.\u201d\nArnold, a husky former all\nAmerican football player who led\nthe Seventh division from Attu to\nOkinawa, said the Americans\nwere having a hard time finding\nKoreans with integrity and ef\nficiency to take over government\njobs from the Japanese.\nAn American who formerly lived\nin Korea is selecting Korean of\nficeholders, he said.\nArnold said that the freedom of\nspeech, press and religion estab\nlished by his forces in the Ameri\ncan zone of Korea applies to Jap\nanese civilians as well as to Ko\nreans.\n\u201cSo long as there are no dis\nturbances harmful to our efforts\nto govern this country,\u201d he said,\n\u201cthe Japanese will enjoy all free\ndom without restraint or discrimi\nnation.\u201d\nUSO CLUBS S E\nBILLION P INS\nSince the United Service Organi\nzation (USO) was established in\n1941, more than a billion persons,\nthe equivalent of almost one-half\nof the world\u2019s entire population,\nhave been served through USO\u2019s\nmany facilities, according to a re\nport today to H. A. Marks, Cam\npaign Chairman of the Community\nWar Chest.\nTotal attendance at USO Camp\nShows, clubs, lounges, and other\nfacilities for troops in transit, at\nArmy and Navy hospitals, and by\nmobile and maneuver services\ncrossed the billion mark on Sep\ntember 1, cumulative figures com\npiled on that date show.\nAudiences aggregating more\nthan 139,000,000 servicemen and\nwomen in all parts of the world\nhave witnessed performances of\nUSO-Camp Shows which are still\ntaking \"made-in-America\u201d brand\nof entertainment to occupation\nforces overseas and to convales\ncents in hospitals throughout the\nUnited Stales.\nAs of September 1, 1,461 USO\nclubs and other facilities staffed\nby the six organizations coopera\ning in the work\u2014YMCA, National\nCatholic Community Service, Na\ntional Jewish Welfare Board,\nYoung Women\u2019s Christian Associa\ntion, Salvation Army and Na\ntional Travelers Air Association\u2014\nwere in operation.\nThe work of USO-Camp Shows,\nmember agencies of the National\nWar Fund, is supported by con\ntributions to the Community War\nChest, Mr. Marks explained.\nThe town of Kenova gets its name\nfrom three states \"Ken\u201d from\nKentucky, \u201cO\u201d from Ohio and \"Va\u201d\nfrom Virginia.\u201d It is on the bor\nders of all .ree states.\nBritish-American Talks\nContinue In Secrecy\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 20.-OI.R)\u2014\nAmerican-British negotiations on\nthe British financial and economic\npreblems continued in utter se\ncrecy today with no prospect of\npublication of the British case uiv\ntil next week.\nBritish officials are working on\nan announcement which will in\nclude the substance of what Brit\nish Economist Lord Keynes has\ntold the American officials. Re\nlease of that announcement has\nbeen delayed by the need for\nchecking some comparative fig\nures, both with the American gov\nernment and with Londan,\nHouse Members In Mood\nTo Grant Greater Powers\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 20\u2014(U.R>\u2014\nThe House appeared today to be\nin a mood to grant President\nTruman broader powers to re\norganize executive agencies than\nit gave the late President Roose\nvelt during peacetime.\nBy unanimous vote the House\nCommittee on Executive Expendi\ntures has approved a bill authoriz\ning Mr. Truman to regroup, coordi\nnate or abolish the bulk of approxi\nmately 100 Executive Agencies\nand their functions.\nCommittee Chairman Carter\nManasco, D., Ala., predicted the\nmeasure will be passed in sub\nstantially its present form by an\noverwhelming house majority.\nNEGROES CHARG I\nWITHJJRGLARIES\nTwo arrests have been made by\ncity detectives in connection with\nthefts from the Yopp Funeral\nHome garage, Joe Brown\u2019s groc\nery store, and the S. and G. Sand\nand Gravel Company garage and\nwill soon prefer charges against\nthe defendants. George Dixon, Jr\u201e\nand Leslie Hayward.\nCity Detective E. B. \u201cRed\u201d Mur\nray, who with Detective J. Wolfe\nand Identification Bureau Super\nintendent Harry Fales investigat\ned the cases, said yesterday morn\ning that a bag of groceries and a\npistol allegedly stolen from\nBrown\u2019s grocery by Dixon, 20\nyear-old Wilmington Negro, had\nbeen recovered. The break-in oc\ncurred on September 16. A war\nrant for Dixon, charging break\ning and entering and larceny and\nreceiving was sworn out.\nBoth Dixon and Hayward, 25\nyear-old Negro. who officers said\nescaped from the Florence, S. C.,\ncounty bureau of identification in\nJune, are charged with breaking\nand entering the Yopp garage and\nstealing two tires, tubes and\nwheels from a hearse housed there\nm September 17. Murray Mid\nhe wheels were found by officer*\nn some woods near Bellevue\n:emetery and the tires and tubes\nvere recovered this morning.\nHayward, the detective contin\nled, also will be charged with\nireaking and entering the S. and\nIt. garage in Sunset Park on\nSeptember 14 and stealing a hy\niraulic jack, which allegedly was\nised to remove the wheels from\nhe hearse. The jack also ha*\nseen recovered.\nThe Negroes are scheduled to\nreceive a preliminary hearing in\nRecorder\u2019s court Tuesday morn\ning. Dixon\u2019s bond was set at\n$500 in court Thursday and Hay\nward, who originally was arrest\ned on vagrancy charges, wa*\nplaced under $1,000 bond.\nOfficer Murray said no arre*t*\nhad been made as yet in connec\ntion with recent robberies at three\ncafes, but action is expected in\nthe immediate future.\nNO CREDIT NEEDED\nCHARLOTTE, Sept. 20.-(AV\nAccording to a statement by Rob\nert M. Hanes of Winston-Salem,\nno further extensoin of govern\nment credit and government guar\nantees of credit are needed. Char\nier banks can and will take care\nsf reconversion needs of the coun\ntry, according to Hanes.\nCLOSED FOR DURATION' AT NAGOYA\nEVERYBODY WAS OUT\u2014and so was everything\u2014when this picture was\nmade at what used to be the Mitsubishi aircraft plant in Nagoya, Japan.\nThe burned-out rubble and ruin were the result of repeated bombings\nby Yank B-29s based on fields in the Marianas. (international;\nMen, Women! Old at\n40,50,60! WantPep?\nWant to Faal Years Youngerf\nDo you blame exhausted, worn-out feeling on ate?\nThousands amazed at what a little pepping up with\nOstrex has done. Contains tonic many need at 40,\n60, 60, for body eld solely because low In Iron; also\nsupplies vitamin Bi, calcium, phosphorus. 35e In\ntroductory nine new only 29c! Try Ostrex Tonic\nTablets for new pep, younger feeling, this very day.\nAt all drug stores everywhtrn\u2014in Wil\nmington. at Saundera.\nHEADACHE\nCspudin, rslievei haadackt\nfwt bacausa it** liquid, lit ia.\ngradient, art alraady dissolved\n\u2014all ready to begin tasing tha\npain. II alia soothe, nervs t\u00abn\nsisa da, l* tha pal*. Usa\n31k, \u00ab0c.\nmi\" jjLyjj iij_\nIf You\nGot Up Nights\nYou Can't fool Night\nBladder\nache, Lef rains,\nPains, Circles Under Byes,\nAnkles, due te non-orsen